The postulated mechanisms of action are still vague and diverse. Secondary metabolites of medicinal mushrooms may produce health benefits and anticancer effects by activating stress resistance mechanisms, including autophagy, DNA repair and expression of antioxidant enzymes (
 Kalaras et al., 2017; 
 Martel et al., 2020). Medicinal mushrooms are recognized as immunomodulators and anti-cancer agents that are able to disrupt certain cellular signal transmission pathways, which are associated with cancer development and progression (
 De Silva et al., 2012). The biochemical mechanisms that mediate this biological activity are still not clearly understood. Several pathways, antiproliferative and immunomodulatory effects triggered by medicinal mushrooms have been described (
 Aras et al., 2018; 
 Ayeka, 2018; 
 Joseph et al., 2018; 
 Rossi et al., 2018). Mushroom polysaccharides are known to stimulate latent natural killer cells, T cells, B cells and macrophage-dependent immune system responses (
 Wasser, 2017). Several species of medicinal mushrooms have shown anti-tumour properties in experimental studies (
 Wasser, 2011). However, much of the evidence is based on results of 
 in vitro assays as well as 
 in vivo animal data (
 De Silva et al., 2012).
